18/ Lastly, in order to enforce a more consistent, on-chain standard for creator fees, weâ€™ve amended the operator filterâ€™s policies to require that contracts deployed after January 2nd implement EIP 2981 as their objective source of truth for creator fee preferences.
17/ To that end, starting January 2nd, 2023, creators that opt out of on-chain creator fee enforcement will be able to set creator fees that are optional for collectors to comply with.
16/ Additionally, weâ€™ve heard compelling pushback from creators on the lack of an alternative mechanism for earning creator fees on OpenSea outside of leveraging our enforcement tool.

15/ We heard the feedback loud and clear that this window of time was not sufficient, so weâ€™ve extended the deadline for when new collections will be required to comply with the creator fee enforcement standard to January 2nd, 2023 across all EVM chains.
14/ Many creators leverage tools such as @manifoldxyz to deploy collections â€” and those tools needed more time to adjust to our new policy.
13/ Initially, collections launched after November 8th were required to implement filtering of creator fee-evading marketplaces in order to set enforced creator fees on OpenSeaâ€¦
12/ As part of this change, weâ€™ve made a few adjustments to OpenSeaâ€™s creator fees policy to accommodate feedback weâ€™ve heard over the past month. More on that below â¬‡ï¸
11/The next steps will be hard, but they're critical. We need your help â€” so come join the conversation: https://t.co/tHVo7wMk19

10/ Weâ€™re glad to join in this effort with our colleagues across the industry. We also emphatically welcome @blur_io, @looksrare, and @sudoswap to revert their stances on creator fee avoidance and join the conversation as members of CORI.

9/ Our hope is that bringing the conversation into a more public and inclusive forum can reduce the thrash industry players have experienced, and can build more community buy-in for the spaceâ€™s evolving standards around creator fees.

8/ Our number one goal is to incentivize a shift in the industry back towards respecting creator fees universally â€” so that on-chain enforcement tools can become an option for some, but not a requirement for all.

7/ This has been a very hard month for the community, and we acknowledge that at times the choices we made were hasty and unaccommodating to some creatorsâ€™ needs. There are ultimately no perfect solutions to the industryâ€™s drift away from respecting creator fees.

6/ Weâ€™re proud to partner with the group originally behind https://t.co/0SEGmsYTOp to spearhead the initial governance of the registry. Soon, weâ€™ll be expanding governance of the registry to include more stakeholders, including â€” critically â€” voices in the creator community.

5/ The charter of CORI is to create a decentralized body tasked with:
- Open, transparent governance of the existing Operator Filter registry and the policies that surround it
- â€œBuilt in publicâ€ R&D focused on improving mechanisms for creator fee enforcement in the future

4/ The tool is very much a v1, and we acknowledge that there are flaws that need to be addressed as we iterate further. 

Our first step towards a better v2 is to decentralize management and governance of the registry â€” initially, by granting control of it to CORI.

3/ Itâ€™s an existential imperative for the space to preserve creator fees. Recently, OpenSea took a step intended to protect them by releasing an on-chain enforcement tool called the Operator Filter.

2/ The revolutionary potential of creator fees has been under attack for months. Marketplaces that do not respect creator fees have been rapidly growing in prominence, and creators, in turn, have seen their effective creator fees severely diminished.

Before Jan 2nd, OpenSea will transfer ownership of the Operator Filter Registry to a multi-sig controlled by a collective incl. @ourzora @manifoldxyz @foundation @superrare @niftygateway & @opensea.

12/ We care DEEPLY about enabling users to operate safely on our platform. Allowing the sale of stolen items and operating with stolen goods is no sign of a healthy ecosystem...but neither is a lack of trust from those of you who got us here.

8/ 2nd, weâ€™re making it easier for users who reported an item stolen to re-enable buying and selling when they recover the item OR determine they should withdraw their stolen item report. For example, we're finalizing details on a simplified process that doesn't require a notary.

7/ For all reports going forward, if we don't receive a police report within 7 days, weâ€™ll re-enable buying & selling for the reported item. This change will help prevent false reports. We think this is a good 1st step & weâ€™re grateful for the communityâ€™s suggestions.

6/ Based on your input, weâ€™ve already made the call to adjust elements of how we implement our policy. 1st, we're expanding the ways we use police reports: we've always used them for escalated disputes, but they'll now be used to confirm all theft reports.

Before we roll this out, we wanted to share this with you early and get your feedback. Please let us know what you think.
Collections that are already verified will have a reasonable grace period (e.g. 1 month) to complete the new verification steps to keep their status.
We are also exploring connected account ownership via oAuth to help prevent bad actors from copying legitimate collections.

If it seems too good to be true, it probably is.

Sadly, there are bad actors looking to take advantage of those new to the world of NFTs. If someone offers you something that looks too good to be true, it probably is.

Avoid cold emails and downloading files from strangers.

Itâ€™s best to not interact with emails, files, and QR codes sent by strangers. Attachments of all formats, including PDFs, have been known to contain harmful viruses or malware.

Limit smart contract approvals.

If you're using MetaMask, make sure to review your spending limit when approving transactions. Click â€œEdit on Permissionâ€ and customize the spend limit for each currency.

For more context, check out this thread: https://t.co/gmJe6Fr75l

Use a crypto hardware wallet.

Using a hardware wallet adds another layer of security for your funds and NFTs. Many users tend to go with Ledger or Trezor.

Use Two-Factor Authentication (2FA).

Enable two-factor authentication with apps like Google Authenticator and Authy, and avoid SMS 2FA where possible since it can be vulnerable to attacks.

Never reuse passwords.

Reusing the same password across multiple accounts makes you more vulnerable to account compromises. A password generator or manager like 1Password or LastPass can make life easier if youâ€™re worried about getting lost in a web of special characters.

Never click on unknown or broken links.

Stay vigilant when browsing websites and interacting with others on social media or Discord. Avoid clicking on ads, images, or links sent by strangers.

Make sure your wallet app or extension is the official one.

If youâ€™re downloading a wallet browser extension, make sure to get your link directly from the providerâ€™s website. When downloading an app, check the reviews and developer info to confirm youâ€™re getting the right one.

Never share your secret recovery phrase.

Your walletâ€™s secret recovery phrase is private to you and should never be shared, even with those you trust. OpenSea is not a wallet provider and will never ask for your walletâ€™s secret recovery phrase.

Get support via official channels.

Customer support is never as fast as we want it to be, but soliciting help on social channels or Discord, where OpenSea does not provide official customer support, can make you a target for scammers.

6. Never share your secret recovery phrase (seed phrase).

It's always worth saying again.

5. Report malicious behavior.

If you receive a DM and you have reason to believe it's an impersonator, research the reporting process and have them removed from the platform.

4. DYOR.

Always be cautious and perform due diligence where possible. If something seems too good to be true, it probably is.

3. Get support through Zendesk.

This is the only way to get support from the OpenSea team. We're rapidly hiring new agents because offering first-in-class customer service is a key goal.

To report fraud, pick the 'Trust & Safety' category.

Link: https://t.co/NQ5imyjdA3

2. Don't scan QR codes or click links you don't recognize.

Bad actors will impersonate OpenSea staff, build trust, then ask you to click something when your guard is down.

Stay vigilant.

1. Turn off Discord DMs on the OpenSea server.

Right-click on the server logo in Discord, press 'Privacy Settings', then disable direct messages.

Alternatively, turn off DMs globally by heading to your user settings. This will mean DMs are switched off on all your servers.

We're always taking steps to ensure our users feel safe.

We will never DM your first, ask for your seed phrase, request that you scan a QR code, or invite you to join a group chat or server that isn't linked to on our site.
